Books published by McGraw-Hill[edit]




2008 conference booth



See also: Category:McGraw-Hill books

McGraw-Hill maintained a general publishing division for some years, whose best known book was the (unpublished) Autobiography of Howard Hughes, a fake biography of Howard Hughes by Clifford Irving, which caused a scandal at the time.
The McGraw-Hill Building[edit]




1221 Avenue of the Americas, former McGraw-Hill headquarters


Main article: 1221 Avenue of the Americas
The company was based at 1221 Avenue of the Americas, otherwise known as the McGraw-Hill Building, until July 2015.[1]
The building in New York City has received prominent attention. In April 2008, surveillance camera footage was released of Nicholas White, a production manager for BusinessWeek (then published by McGraw-Hill) who was trapped in the building's elevator for 41 hours in October 1999.[31]
Connection to the family of George W. Bush[edit]
The McGraws and the George W. Bush family have close ties dating back several generations. Harold McGraw Jr. (deceased) was a member of the national grant advisory and founding board of the Barbara Bush Foundation for Family Literacy.[32]
McGraw-Hill Federal Credit Union[edit]
Established in 1935, the McGraw-Hill Federal Credit Union originally served employees of the McGraw-Hill companies in New York City only.[33] The credit union moved from its location inside the McGraw-Hill building to East Windsor, New Jersey, in 2005. Its accounts are insured by the National Credit Union Administration. It provides savings, checking accounts, CDs, money-market accounts, IRAs, credit cards, auto loans, and home mortgages.
Awards[edit]
In 1999, the National Building Museum presented the McGraw-Hill Companies with its annual Honor Award for the corporation's contributions to the built environment.[34]
